data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with modern MSTest 3.x+ assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Original | Replacement | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" instead of "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle()` | Returns the element directly; clear failure if 0 or 2+ match |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` line is fine staying as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API, and the intent is already clear.
